The Negroes catched at the Propoſal, and the Scheme was communicated by them to John Hughſon, who kept a Publick Houſe by the North River in this City, a Place where Numbers of Negroes uſed to reſort, and be entertained privately (in Defiance of the Law
                  •
               ) at all Hours, as appeared afterwards, and will be ſhewn at large in the enſuing Sheets: Thither they uſed to bring ſuch Goods as they ſtole from their Maſters or others, and Hughſon, his Wife and Family, received them: There they held a Conſultation with Hughſon and his Family, how they ſhould act in order to compaſs the Attainment of this Booty.

A Diſcovery was made in the Morning early, that ſome Coals had been put under a Hayſtack, ſtanding near the Coach-Houſe and Stables of Joſeph Murray, 
                  Eſq; in the Broad Way, and near ſome Dwelling Houſes there, which had it them Fire, would have been in great Danger;


but the Coals went out of themſelves, as ſuppoſed, having only ſinged ſome Part of the Hay. It was ſaid, there were Coals and Aſhes traced along from the Fence to a neighbouring Houſe next adjoining the Stables, which cauſed a Suſpicion of the Negro that lived there.

