q.p:
THAT about five Months ago being at Comfort's on a Holliday, he met there Jack and Cook (COMFORT's) and Harry (FURMAN's) and Comfort's old Negro Woman; That Jack and Cook went out of the Houſe and left him with Harry, who aſked him if he would not be concerned with them, in helping them to kill the white People? Which was all that paſſed at that Time; and he never had any other Meeting with them afterwards; nor did any of them ever after talk with him on that Subject; 
                                       ••
                                    d that this is all that he knew of the Plot.

div.p:
                                    TOBY (Widow Breaſted's) ſaid, 
                                    That Chriſtmaſs Hollidays Cook, Comfort's, carried him to Hughſon's, where he ſaw Ben, Mr. Jay's; Ben, Capt. Marſhall's, and ſome others, who all ſupped there; That he ſaw Hughſon, his Wife, &c. there. That Ben, Jay's, prevailed on him to kiſs the Book; that he accordingly did kiſs it; that thereupon Ben ſaid, he was his Man, and ſhould ſtand to him, but did not tell him for what;


but ſeeing him afterwards, he told him, he had ſwore to fight the white People, and ſtand by him: That the Priſoner promis'd, and Ben bid him bring him a Piſtol to Mr. Jay's Garden, and told him that they had bought ſome Arms already, and by and by they'd riſe. The Negroes then preſent [beſides] were Cook, Comfort's; Cato, Cowley's; Cuffee, Philipſe's; Quack, Rooſevelt's.

